<header id="title">
  <h1>Fritz Zwicky</h1>
</header>
<main id="main">
  <p>Fritz Zwicky was a man of science, he, along with a colleague, named supernovas, theorized the origin of cosmic rays, and he thought of the dark matter before anyone else did. I'm sure most of us have heard througout lives of his discoveries in our education, but not so much about his name. I recently watched the Cosmos show with Neil De Grasse Tyson where he explains a bit of the dark matter and since Zwicky's name isn't popular -I mean outside of the science field-, I thought of writing about him even if just a bit. </p>
    <figure id="img-div">
      <img id="image" src="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/BppqxAdCYAEalhu.jpg" alt="Zwicky Fritz in a funny pose">
      <figcaption id="img-caption">Zwicky Fritz seems like a fun guy!</figcaption>
    </figure>
  <section id="tribute-info" class="life">
    <section class="beginning">
      <h2>Beginning</h2>
      <p>Zwicky was born in Bulgaria in 1898, to a Swiss father and a Czech mom, he was the oldest of six brothers.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="studies">
      <h2>Studies</h2>
      <p>In 1922, he received a physics doctorate from the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology, ZÃ¼rich. Later, in 1925 he went to the United States to work at the California Institute of Technology (Caltech).</p>
    </section>
    <section class="personal-life">
      <h2>Personal Life</h2>
      <p>His mother died in 1927, he got married in 1932 to Dorothy Vernon Gates, and divorced in 1941. He got married again in 1947 to Anna Margaritha Zurcher with whom he had three daughters. In 1974 he died in the U.S.A., and was buried in Switzerland.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="work">
      <h2>Some of his work</h2>
      <p>Some of his work includes:
        <ul>
          <li>Supernovae and neutron stars</li>
          <li>Gravitational lenses</li>
          <li>Dark matter</li>
          <li>Tired light</li>
      </ul>
      Zwicky had an original mind, and many of his ideas were rejected at first and later when discovered they'd remember his name.</p>
  </section>
  </section>
</main>
